data.text:
As a young woman, Princess Anne Antoinette Françoise Charlotte of Bourbon-Parma did not expect to have to earn a living as a shop assistant in New York. She and her family had fled there after the Nazis invaded Denmark, her homeland, in 1940. Her father, Prince René of Bourbon-Parma, was obliged to find work with a gas company while her mother, HRH Princess Margrethe of Denmark, made hats.

This indignity did not last long, however, and the princess soon found a more heroic form of employment when she returned to Europe to serve with the Free French army as an ambulance driver in Casablanca, Algiers and Italy.
